    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_3366596691" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3366596691" />
    <a title="Charles" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13904332-charles"><img alt="Charles" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614474028p2/13904332.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3366596691?book_show_action=true">Apr 08, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Charles" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Charles" href="/user/show/13904332-charles">Charles</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3366596691" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer102744577885083921">In my opinion, Alistair MacLeod’s tender portrayals of the Canadian East Coast remain unsurpassed. <br/><br/>A good decade ago, <i>The Lost Salt Gift of Blood</i> had bowled me over with its love of the land and its people, its bits of Gaelic thrown in out of reverence toward the old countries – a song’s verse here, a saying there, nothing in excess or without context – and the ordinary lives it depicted so truthfully yet with so much inspiration. MacLeod wrote his characters not unlike Kent Haruf might have, fo</span>
  <span id="freeText102744577885083921" style="display:none">In my opinion, Alistair MacLeod’s tender portrayals of the Canadian East Coast remain unsurpassed. <br /><br />A good decade ago, <i>The Lost Salt Gift of Blood</i> had bowled me over with its love of the land and its people, its bits of Gaelic thrown in out of reverence toward the old countries – a song’s verse here, a saying there, nothing in excess or without context – and the ordinary lives it depicted so truthfully yet with so much inspiration. MacLeod wrote his characters not unlike Kent Haruf might have, for instance, or Richard Yates; the time and place differed, that’s all.<br /><br />Now, the same way <i>The Lost Salt Gift of Blood</i> (1976) had featured short stories that never truly left my heart, <i>As Birds Bring Forth the Sun and Other Stories</i> (1986) just delivered a fresh new batch of them. My heart feels so full it may well burst. While I’m under the impression that the first collection was a smidge more powerful, this second one lacks nothing of the lore or the insight that had first won me over and that’s to mention nothing of MacLeod’s gifted writing. <br /><br />Every single time I pick up something by this author, I come to the realization that the last time I thought “Now here’s someone who captures what it is to be from the East Coast at its very core” was the last time I read… him, again. <br /><br /><i>There was a time long ago when the lobsters were not thought to be so valuable. Probably because the markets of the larger world had not yet been discovered or were so far away. People then ate all they wanted of them and even used them for fertilizer on their fields. And those who did eat them did not consider them to be a delicacy. There is a quoted story from the time which states that in the schools you could always identify the children of the poor because they were the ones with lobster in their sandwiches. The well-to-do were able to afford bologna.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="102744577885083921" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

